,Recommended,225080,8380119,"Posted: 28 December, 2013",all,Vlad,"A rare gem of a game based on a modest concept that is executed flawlessly. It doesn't try to appeal to everyone and is better for it. Its main strength is its highly emotional story which is hard to talk about without spoiling anything. I can only say that it managed to surprise me more than once. It's about 3 hours long which might seem short on paper but you won't be bored for a single minute and the impact it makes will stay with you a great deal longer. It's designed to be played as a ""single player co-op game"" but I played it with my younger brother for an extra layer of immersion and we both had a wonderful time throughout. The game doesn't actually ""need"" a controller to work but using a keyboard is a bad idea as it takes away much of the gameplay value. I had to use an emulator to get my old controller to work with the game but it was well worth the trouble. All in all I'd say it's more than worth the price and the 3 hours of your life as it will most likely enchant your whole evening like it did mine."
,Recommended,225080,10829918,"Posted: 26 June, 2014",all,Baby Spice,"In first hour of gameplay, I've thrown a little girls ball down the well, got my petty revenge on ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ who made my life difficult, stole not one, but two sheeps and made friends with a benevolent troll.Brothers: A Tale of Two Sons combines a brillianty crafted, surprisingly interactive world, with charming, sympathetic characters and emotional storyline. It's short and very linear, but it's also airtight, perfectly paced and not a moment of it feels superfluous. While platforming is easy and puzzle soultions are almost always very obvious, main challenge comes from mastering games unique dual-control gameplay (you control one brother with each analog stick and that's why GAMEPAD IS A MUST). To me it was relatively easy but some less patient players may be discouraged from properly enjoying it. However, that would be to their own detriment, because despite it's shortness (and subsequently relatively high price) it provides a unique experience and narrative (reactions and dialogue are communicated exclusively through mime and vocal inflections) which should be experienced and appreciated by anyone who loves puzzle-adventures or just wants a well-crafted, story driven game."
,Recommended,225080,8483673,"Posted: 1 January, 2014",all,Praxis-[CE],"This was probably one of the best games I've ever played in all my years of gaming. Great story, amazing graphics, beautiful music, and very rewarding to play. Although people have found ways to make it work without one, you will definitely need a controller to get the full experience (preferably one with feedback/vibration turned on and also 2 analog sticks, I used an Xbox 360 controller).It's a very short game and probably doesn't have a lot of replay value (though I personally may want to play through it again and again every so often, the way you go back and read a book you really love every few years), but it's an experience that I think will stay with you long after you finish playing.At first, I thought the controls were going to be awkward, but the interface is so simple and the story is so compelling that you really do get lost in the game and the controls feel very natural. The puzzles are intuitive and not too difficult, and unlike a lot of games I never found myself frustrated because something was too hard or I couldn't figure out what the next step was. I also never felt like the puzzles were too repetitive (even though some elements do repeat) because the environment keeps changing enough to keep things interesting.Overall this game was a pleasure to play and very very satisfying. If you're on the fence about buying it, don't hesitate. It's a beautiful gaming experience that shouldn't be missed."
,Recommended,225080,34356115,Posted: 19 August,all,桃味,"Warning: do not be fooled by its beautiful graphics, this game has a dark story.When I was half way through the game I thought the developers must have been a bunch of antisocial psychopaths. It was only after I had completed it did I change my opinion.This a game about love, courage, growing up and moving on.According to World Health Organisation, the global average life span in 2015 was 71.4 years.The idea of we living too long unnerves me sometimes. Throughout that 71.4 years we have, we meet too many people, we develop too many relationships, we become especially fond of some of them, and we lose them in the end.It could never be easy, losing someone you once held dear, or parting ways with someone for whom you still care.And that is why the ending of this game got me so much.I am still afraid, but I, too, will learn to be courageous.They must set out upon a journey to find and bring back the ""Water of Life"" as they come to rely on one another to survive. One must be strong where the other is weak, brave where the other is fearful, they must be... Brothers.I’ll be braver than before, since you are no longer here for me to rely on."
,Recommended,225080,8679305,"Posted: 12 January, 2014",all,Senno,"Brothers: A Tale of Two Sons opens and closes with death. It’s a game about death. But it isn’t a game about killing. What is between the opening and closing scenes is a dark fairytale world full of mature themes, and the bond of two siblings as they struggle valiantly on a quest to save their withering father. A beautiful and melancholic journey awaits you, and a deep emotional investment will be required. And though brief, this attractive storybook adventure is as dreamlike as it is affecting.Brothers’ appeal lies in what it doesn’t tell you. Cutscenes are used sparingly, with the world itself providing the emotional pull and story. For instance, while I was using the twin-control scheme to explore a town, I was able to steal a ball and throw it down a well, leaving a small girl in tears. The imaginary language used by the characters is universally bolstered by wonderful body language, and the affection and fears that each brother holds for the other.The twin-control scheme is key to the game’s identity. It’s a somewhat clumsy control system, with each brother being assigned to a control stick and a shoulder button. However, Brothers’ generally requires the input of both characters, both to work together and independently, to pass obstacles. It’s a key identifying feature for the game and one that has been cleverly exploited.The obstacles are generally rather easy, and there is only a small amount of room to experiment, with generally one rather obvious solution. The challenge comes in actually performing the actions necessary to pass. As you control both brothers at the same time, and often you need to split them up to do individual tasks, some of which can be timed, it can occasionally feel like trying to pat your head and rub your belly at once. Something that for most of us, we are certainly capable, but it does require a different type of input than we would normally use.And these siblings will certainly have you wringing your hands. Sometimes over the controls, but mostly over their relationship with each other, and in turn, your relationship with them. The epic undertaking they’re on will have them trek over snow-capped mountains, across frozen lakes and an ancient giant’s battlefield – it’s a wonderfully realised world without exposition – it exists and feels real. The settings are as varied as the tasks required of the brothers, and the emotional pull of the game will have you powering on to see what happens next. This is not a game to be played in short stretches, and at just over 3 hours in my playthrough, I completed it in just two sittings.The dark undercurrent of death in this world is never confrontational, it seeps into every pore of the game, and can even be missed. Shortly after leaving a small village, I passed a man attempting to hang himself. Using one brother to prop him up, and another to cut the rope, I left him sitting beneath the tree to sob like a man who had nothing left. Further ahead I found a burnt out homestead, and with the brothers working in tandem, I was able to retrieve a small music-box which seemed to help the man. This sentimental scene is one of many throughout Brothers’ that outright dealt with death in a mature and intelligent fashion, an unusual but fascinating design decision by the developers.I suppose you could say that the true aim of Brothers’ is to make us feel. Of course, there is the adventure, and the smartly designed environmental obstacles, but this is a game where touch isn’t just an afterthought, and death has some permanence, and has some resonance. And while it’s brief, Brothers’ doesn’t outstay it’s welcome, and provides an ambitious, emotionally affecting adventure that while short, is very sweet. Memorable.8.5/10."
