76561198080038125,Recommended,225080,12567052,"Posted: 19 October, 2014",all,Hexvex,"Rating: 10/10 must buy - worth full price and then some ( WORK OF ART status)Summary: Emotionally charged and beautifully designed adventure puzzle game. Can be played without controller but dont do it, use a 2 stick controller. Hits right in the feelings in the best possible way. No one will be left unmoved by the game.Long review (SPOILER FREE):Game is set in a fantasy world in which you play as two brothers on a epic quest to acquire a certain item. It is a very mature tale about growing up, brotherly bonds, effects of  trauma on a young person, overcoming those traumas and acceptance of death as part of life.Art direction is really good and make the world seem very alive which in turn makes you get really immersed in the game. Game is not long around 2,5h (4h if you stop to take in scenery) but in that short time it will take you on a emotional roller coaster ranging from heartwarming to heartbreaking. You will not feel like you were cheated by how short it is in the end, it will feel perfectly timed.I can honestly say this is one of the few games that ever induced such deep emotions and cathartic feeling at the end. I am talking about The Walking Dead Clementine affection or MGS Sniper Wolf death scene level of emotions. This game will stick with me for the rest of my life. Please play this game in ONE sitting.Characters in this game speak in a made up language and there are no subtitles yet design is so masterful you will never not understand what is happening or get lost or not understand a puzzle. In fact i was impressed that i developed such strong feelings for the brothers despite it. Puzzles range from easy to medium. Sometimes they are a bit ""hard"" just because you are most likely not used to controlling 2 characters at once using both analog sticks and R2 L2 triggers. Personally i did not find them clunky it worked really well for such a design.Most impressive thing that really hit me in the feels was how the game  managed to incorporate emotions into actuall controls. That blew my mind and if you play until the end you will know what i mean by that.Only criticism i can possibly give would be that you should have a controller. Everything else is perfect at least for me. I will follow future similar releases from this studio. This game is a work of interactive art that can not be done in any other medium except video gaming.GO BUY IT !!!"
,Recommended,225080,11852314,"Posted: 24 August, 2014",all,Insane Wizard,A game where nothing bad happened ever
,Recommended,225080,8945732,"Posted: 1 February, 2014",all,PensiveMuffin,"I love absolutely everything about Brothers.1. It's a rejection of every condescending trend in game design from the past 5 years. No hand-holding, no collectables, no constant pats on the back. This is a game that treats its players like adults. Your *special reward* for playing Brothers is the WONDROUS JOY of playing Brothers.2. The developers knew their constraints and made smart decisions with the resources they had. No budget for voice actors? That's fine, the characters will speak their own language. XBLA games have limited graphics? Screw it, we'll pick an art style that looks good at any poly count.3. Did I say ""looks good""? Sorry, I meant GORGEOUS. Brothers is flat out beautiful. You'll find yourself constantly stopping to take in jaw-dropping vistas. The game knows it too. The designers sprinkled benches throughout whose only purpose are to let your characters relax and admire the view.4. No English, no problem. You don't need to understand the characters' words to get what they're saying. Everything you need to know comes across in tone, body language, and action. Brothers is the ultimate rejection of the David Cage school of videogame emotion. You don't need to see the individual atoms of NaCl and H2O in a character's tears to inspire empathy.5. I adored the coming-of-age theme. It's done in a way that's entirely unique to the medium, and yet I've never seen another game pull it off the way Brothers does. The game begins in innocence. You're running across verdant hills and through lush fields, playing pranks on local farmers, dodging mean dogs.But the darkness slowly creeps in. First, it's only in the background, and easily ignored by our storybook children on their magical adventure. Soon, though, you'll be neck-deep in the muck, and the green grass will be nothing but a distant memory.For such a short game (3-4 hours), it's incredible to compare where you begin and where you end up. It's the journey in between, the way that the protagonists react in the face of an increasingly adult world, and how they ultimately  learn to live in it—that's what makes Brothers so special."
