,Recommended,225080,368654,"Posted: 16 September, 2013",all,Citizenkane,"Brothers is one of the first games which I think can be universally regarded as a work of art. It should speak volumes that my father, a man who has never played a single video game, or even picked up a controller, sat down for four hours to play Brothers through to the end.The aesthetic rivals the beauty of Trine 2. The difficulty curve and pacing rival the perfect execution of Portal. The storytelling rivals To the Moon. For anybody with a head and a heart this game is a must play."
76561198045189283,Recommended,225080,21306845,"Posted: 18 February, 2016",all,Lifemicrorez,"This game made me cry. Twice.Which is a good thing - I like it when fictional stuff elicits tears from my eyes; I call it ‘resonating with art’. (What? It’s better than that ‘ninjas cutting onions’ cliche people always use... right?)On the subject of cliches, this game has many: a convenient sunset, a generic premise to set up a generic conflict, a flashback recalling happier times, and at some point a backstabber.The game is also linear, and short (3 hours). But hey, sometimes it’s fun to play a linear and short game. (People complain about linearity, but if every game had an open world, well, we’d have a dump truck-full of terrible open-world games.)The difference with this game is that its linearity serves a purpose: there’s a constant build-up, and just the faintest sense of a ticking clock, of inevitability.Even the cliches add rather than detract; they make the story seem innocent, the adventure seem mild, the characters seem... invincible. They keep things straight-forward, because straight and forward is precisely where the game wants you to go. Even the controls, which will take time to adjust to, are as basic as they get.But for all its simplicity, Brothers doesn’t let you grow bored. There’s never two of the same puzzle, and the settings change regularly. (I have a short attention span, but this game never once lost its magic.) You might ‘die’ a few times, but you’re never really stuck, and even in the few places where a sense of urgency might be felt, there’s never much tension. It’s the kind of game that you can play at leisure, while also being very fun.The setting, mind you, will at some point take an abrupt turn - in literal terms, you’ll start to go downhill instead of up - and from there the mood will start to shift. Just wait.Everything, from the settings to the cliches, will there reveal itself as a tool, a gameplay feature employed by the developer to serve a purpose - but it’s a purpose I shan’t spoil. Even the controller, which you’d spent a decent time mastering, will turn out to have, all along, been a pawn expertly positioned in storytelling.Towards the end every piece will culminate like a well-choreographed dance, a superbly-structured film. And in many ways this game is a film, but it’s the kind of film that the developer goes to lengths to make sure you’re a part of. Enjoy it.Because you may not want to play this game twice. You’ll certainly want others to play it, to experience it with child-like eyes; but you’ll also wish that you could return to when your own eyes were child-like - when, you might say, times were happier. Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons is just one of those games that you can never un-play.10/10P.S. I purchased this game on sale (80% off, I think). Whether you think it's worth the full price will depend on if, for the same price, you'd purchase a 3-hour film that you knew would be great to watch."
,Recommended,225080,13631394,"Posted: 26 December, 2014",all,Mhoku,"Breathtaking game.When I first sat down to play this, I was immediately drawn to the characters and the story. The fact that the emotional attatchment to each of these characters grows so quickly and you understand what each brother is going thru is astounding. All without ever speaking an actual language.Story aside the complexity of the puzzles gradually scales as you play the game in a seamless fashion. The mechanics work quite well with the unique control scheme they have going for them. If your not used to controllers it may be a bit troublesome but by the harder puzzles you will feel very comfortable with your dextarity.Graphics wise looks great for what it is the art style fits perfect with the atmosphere of the game.Bought this once on xbox bought it yet again on PC9.5/10"
,Recommended,225080,24314760,"Posted: 14 July, 2016",all,Geekrider,"Jesus Christ! This game! It is one of the best visually breathtaking and emotional game I have probably ever played. I felt everything between joy and sadness. I laughed, I cried, I was stunned and I was angry. The set pieces are amazing, the music pulls your heart strings and the characters are compelling even though they speak gibberish (It's a fictional language like the Sims). Don't get fooled by the nonsensical dialog though. Every action and emotions plays out perfectly well and drags you deeper into the game. A message to my 3 brothers. I love you guys. Even though we don't show it to each other.11/10"
,Recommended,225080,24201624,"Posted: 9 July, 2016",all,Kaleith,"Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons is often named as one of the best example of games that use the tools proper of the video game medium in a way that no other does.The main ""gimmick"" of the game is the fact that you control the titular two brothers at once, using one analog control stick and one ""action"" button for each.This mechanic, alien at first, quickly becomes second nature, letting you fully enjoy your travels through beautiful scenery following the brothers on a quest to find a cure for their dying father.Talking about storytelling, that's another way Brothers sets itself apart from most other games, as the simple, fable-like story is told using gameplay and rare in-engine cutscenes.You find out the personality and quirks of each brother by the way they interact with each other and with the people and creatures they encounter during the journey. You understand the power of their brotherly bond by the way they help each other out solving puzzles or getting out of difficult situations. All of this without ever having to read or hear a single word.I would 100% recommend Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons if it wasn't already clear enough, as the way the game marries its storytelling to its mechanics is truly fascinating and definitely worth the 2 to 4 hours needed to complete it."
,Recommended,225080,9676689,"Posted: 30 March, 2014",all,Noov,"Absolutely outstanding. Best use of gameplay mechanics serving and assisting the story I have ever seen; emotionally manipulative as hell, yes, but nothing short of amazing.Everything in this game seems crafted towards detail, every small thing seems to be there because of an artistic purpose behind it. Finishing the game is like putting down a book that had you absolutely enthralled for weeks; you get that empty feeling because it's all over and there's nothing more to experience, and you're sad to leave the amazing universe you were immersed in, however only after leaving it can you truly appreciate how amazing the whole journey was.God dang, this was a great game. I'd wax poetry about it for ages on end if I could."
