,Recommended,225080,34806223,Posted: 7 September,all,FichteFoll,"Brothers is quite short (3-3.5h), but very enjoyable with a great narrative relying entirely on gestures and tone. It does not rely on any words at all, excluding explanations on controls. The characters do talk, but you are not supposed to understand them, and you really don't need to either.The story is simple but effective. You probably already read it in the game's description. That's about it.The gameplay of solving puzzles and basic platforming with two characters at once is not challenging but unusual and it takes some getting used to. However, it is fun throughout the entire time and does not get boring the slightest. The game *can* be played with a keyboard, but you really shouldn't; it was made for a controller.The soundtrack is very sweet and the scenery is quite immersive, covering a large variety of environments in such a short time. Graphics aren't top-notch but it doesn't bother me at all.Since it is a few years old now, you can easily get it during a sale, which makes up for the short gameplay."
76561197973133158,Recommended,225080,8568392,"Posted: 4 January, 2014",all,[8HN] Chair?,"At the start of the game, I was enthralled with the art style. Through the middle I was continually impressed at the creativity, originality, and storytelling. By the end, I was sure I'd just experienced one of the best games I've ever played. At the risk of getting carried away or sounding too hyperbolic, the question of whether games can be art has been put to rest.It took me about 3 hours to complete. I mention it because, in this case, I consider that the perfect length. It is as long it needed to be; no more, no less. Long enough to be a great experience, with no unnecessary ""filler."" More importantly, it is short enough that you have no excuse to not see it through to completion.Were I doing a more clinical breakdown, I might mention great choices on the part of the developers, like having no HUD to distract or pull the player out of the experience. Or the fantastic art and sound design. Or the fact that they respected players' brains enough to let us infer the finer points of the story through context and body language, rather than beating us over the head with exposition. Or, perhaps most impressively, the way they use the controls themselves to great effect. (On that note, ""Brothers"" really deserves the proper playing environment: preferrably a gamepad with dual analog thumbsticks. If you don't have an Xbox 360 pad for PC, but you do own a modern gaming console, consider purchasing it on your console of choice instead. The controls are that important, in my opinion.)Since this ISN'T a clinical breakdown, however, I'll simply say that ""Brothers"" deserves a few hours of your time."
