,Recommended,225080,33426273,Posted: 10 July,all,Endyo,"Brothers – A Tale of Two Sons is an experience, first and foremost.  It's a story told without words through the medium of a well crafted game.  One that you may identify with, or one that at least resonates with the general nature of humanity.   That's all before you even get to the reality of the mechanics having the player control two characters simultaneously with an analog stick dedicated to each.  Which ends up creating some of the most imaginative gameplay of its time.It's important to identify Brothers for what it is up front for those that may not be compelled to 'experience' game rather than simply play it.  You'll take control of two brothers set out on a journey in the same vein as other adventure games.  You can do little else in the process but guide them to various positions where they can hit triggers to perform other actions, such as climbing, turning a crank, or moving an object.   Each brother has specific traits, such as the older one being taller and stronger and the younger being smaller, which is advantageous for getting in to tight spaces.  These traits will be used in a variety of ways, both separately and together, to solve puzzles that you come up against in your progression through the game.  That is what you're actually going to be doing from start to finish.  It's not particularly difficult in any respect, once you figure out how to control both brothers at the same time effectively, it's more a matter of being able to solve puzzles that, by design, won't leave you struggling.However, Brothers exists less to be a demo of a neat control scheme and more to tell a story of two siblings set out to find a cure for their father's sickness.  Their journey has them meeting all sorts of friendly, indifferent, and sometimes vicious characters that weave their way in to the story and the expedition.  As you navigate through the town in which you start and move further and further from your home, you find increasingly majestic and mysterious lands that sometimes fill your screen with strange creatures or grand visages.  Each corner you turn could be a whole new realm more spectacular than the last, and each step may lead you in to another puzzle to solve before you can dive in.You may look at the time I have played this game and the time others have as well and think it's short.  That's not an incorrect perception, but the game isn't designed to be challenging or replayable.  The developers goal seems to be for it to connect with you on an emotional level and tell a great story in a unique universe.  That may only take three or four hours of your time, but when you're finished you will have something to look back on with appreciation for being able to be a part of it.  I don't think that it would have had as much of an impact of the game was significantly longer or more difficult.Brothers – A Tale of Two Sons is a game I think anyone that finds value in a strong narrative and great environment design should purchase.  It's an old game now, but I played it well after release and still found it to be well worth the time.  Also, as far as the pricing, while it may have a base price of $14.99, it is regularly on sale for as little as $1.49.   For that price, it's worth it just to see if you are one of the many that plays this game and comes away with it making an mark in your life.If you'd like to see more of my reviews, check out my curator page here:http://steamcommunity.com/groups/EndyoGaming#curation"
,Recommended,225080,9097610,"Posted: 13 February, 2014",all,Jragghen,"An excellent, if short, game. The game is almost entirely story, and is told without the use of words as two brothers travel through a world helping one another to pass various obstacles. The specatcle is largely the point of the game, and the graphics are suitably awe-inspiring to allow it to work. Controls can be slightly awkward sometimes, as one half of your controller controls each brother individually - there will be times where having them on the wrong side of one another will confuse you for a half second or so - but the entire game plays seamlessly and is a wonderful experience that everyone should enjoy at least once."
,Recommended,225080,9769098,"Posted: 9 April, 2014",all,Jammerlee,"It has been a very long time since a game managed to make me cry... this one had me sobbing.Prepare yourself for this emotional rollercoaster - this game is both as beautiful and atmospheric as it is heartwrenching. Having just lost their mother to drowning at sea, and now on the verge of losing their gravely ill father, the two titular brothers set off on a surreal journey to obtain the one thing able to cure him. The story unfolds without words (at least, not words that are comprehensible), using body language, music and nuance in a manner that is masterfully handled and pulls you straight in.Gameplay, unfortunately, is where Brothers suffers. Firstly, you NEED to use an Xbox 360 controller. Each brother is controlled individually with each control stick, proving to have a steep learning curve. This essentially gives an illusion of co-op, which while visually interesting and making both of their movements feel organic (rather than an NPC programmed to follow you), it proves to be quite frustrating at first as you frequently lose track of which stick controls which brother. Another downside is that it's also quite short and can be finished in only a few hours.Atmosphere, story and visuals are this game's bread and butter. Despite the frustrating gameplay, if you're fond of games strong on story that tug at your heartstrings and leave you thinking long after the credits have rolled, I can't recommend this highly enough."
