,Recommended,225080,8387783,"Posted: 28 December, 2013",all,Yooka-Laylee,"First things first: the store page isn't kidding when it says you'll want an Xbox controller or equivalent. Keyboard controls are available, but a recurring puzzle in the game requires you to rotate both control sticks which for obvious reasons becomes a major pain when you aren't using a controller.Overall, I enjoyed this game. It's the closest thing a game can get to being a movie without ceasing to be a game, and it's done quite well. The storyline's very well-written and executed, and the graphics are similarly good and styled in just the right way to boost your immersion into the story (most of the time). The controls are solid, the camera generally does its job (except when you're shimmying on top of a narrow ledge) and the puzzles are intuitive.That's not to say there aren't flaws. The graphics, being generally good, only ended up killing my immersion on the occasions theyweren't; examples include a flock of 2D bats in the glider section and footprints that appeared everywhere but where I was actualy stepping in the snowy area.Since this is a heavily story-driven game, it's linear and fairly short (still more than twice as long as your average movie, though). If there's a side path, it either joins up with the main path within a short amount of time or exists solely to provide an achievement. It's usually pretty obvious what you're supposed to do, so there isn't a whole lot of challenge to the game; if you're the kind of gamer who can't stand games that don't kill you for breathing too hard, I wouldn't pick this game up.The few times itisn'tclear what you need to do end up extremely grating by contrast; two of these particularly got on my nerves. First, there's a glider segment where your glider gets torn apart , and aiming at the nearest landmass ends up getting you killed and makes you do the entire (2 minute) glider section all over again. Second, near the end of the game there's a segment where you have to get Little Bro (who can't swim) across a body of water while Big Bro isn't close enough to help; to find the solution, you literally have to mash buttons.I also encountered several glitches, many of which forced me to restart from a checkpoint; feel free to check out my screenshot gallery for examples. (And one spoiler, though it's properly tagged.) Fortunately, they didn't happen more than once per location, and were very infrequent.Despite these flaws, I found that the game was enjoyable and worth its $5 price tag, especially since I approached the game from the perspective of it being an interactive movie."
