76561197972600983,Recommended,225080,8439698,"Posted: 30 December, 2013",all,MasterOfUnlocking,"Wow. Just wow. If you like emotionally involving games with strong art design, unique gameplay and interesting stories you simply HAVE to play this game. Trust me. You won't regret it."
,Recommended,225080,7534468,"Posted: 31 October, 2013",all,///cl4ym4n.de >:3,"Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons is a beautiful top-down puzzle adventure developed by Swedish developer Starbreeze Studios, who are better known for rather action-heavy games such as Riddick, The Darkness, Syndicate or Payback, so it's definitely a surprise that their first non-shooter game ended up being such a lovingly crafted piece of work.The game tells the moving story of two brothers who set out on a journey across the lands to find a cure for their ailing father. While this is a pretty average story, it is presented with so much strength and emotion that it is really hard not to get touched by it. Even more so due the fact that there is no 'real' voice acting in the game apart from bits and pieces in a made-up language, so every bit of feeling and emotion the game tries to convey is is entirely transported through the fantastic soundtrack, the level design and the character acting.Although the game is based on the PC-friendly Unreal Engine, it doesn't really provide many graphics options aside from brightness, resolution and VSync, but that shouldn't hold you off because the game looks absolutely stunning regardless.The level design is fairly linear, so there is usually just one path to get from A to B, but the varying enviroments are packed with so much detail and love that it is a real pleasure to the eye to just wander around and explore all the tiny details Starbreeze has left in the game, such as a squirrel climbing a tree or bunnies hopping around. You can also sit down on any of the various benches in the levels to get a scenic view of some special spots. Absolutely fantastic.An innovation that I haven't seen in any other game yet are the gameplay mechanics as you control both brothers at once, each brother with one thumb stick on your control, so it's basically like playing a two-player co-op game - but alone. This feels extremely weird at first and will definitely put your coordination and multitasking skills to the test, but the further you get into the game the more you get used to it.The puzzles in the game make use of this mechanic in various ways and while the puzzle solutions as such generally are fairly obvious, solving them by controlling both brothers at once provides the actual challenge.PSA: Despite the fact that the store page mentions 'Notice: Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons requires a controller to play', the game can be played with a keyboard just fine and the launcher also lets you rebind the keys (by default you control one brother with WASD and the other one with the arrow keys). I definitely recommend playing the game with a controller, though, as this simply feels better with a game like this.With roughly 3.5 to 4 hours the game isn't exceptionally long by most people's standard, but it has so much depth and emotion that I consider it worth it every single cent if it manages to leave me with both sadness and satisfaction upon finishing it. If I had known what a strong game this is, I wouldn't have hesitated to pre-order it.Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons is a shiny gem among the games released this year and needs all the attention it can get. Especially these days where games rarely tell such an emotional story - or any story at all."
76561198042097597,Recommended,225080,8182806,"Posted: 21 December, 2013",all,PremiumTree54,"I'm not forgetting this story for a long time. Go play this if you haven't already done so, it's incredible."
,Recommended,225080,8396575,"Posted: 29 December, 2013",all,Stockx,"It's hard to write a good review of a game like Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons without adding spoilers. But don't be afraid to read any further, no spoilers here.Brothers is a pinnacle of game design. It's a perfect combination of narrative, gameplay mechanics that just ""work"", and beautiful design both in level design as in general art style. There were numerous moments where I was just blown away by the beauty of this game. It's something you don't expect in the beginning when you see the Unreal Engine logo.They make up for the low polygon count of the characters by beautiful textures, great lighting effects and the best camera positioning you have ever seen.TL;DR:Short but oh oh oh so sweet. Just have a controller handy (unplayable with keyboard and mouse). Definitely worth it.Tip @ any university/college providing a game design course: This game is the perfect use-case of how it should be."
