76561198229231924,Not Recommended,225080,31305681,Posted: 22 April,all,teufel_barde,"Brothers, a tale of two sons, is a puzzle solving game where you control both characters at once, with a story convayed without any spoken words.The story is simple, two brothers are trying to cure their dad of mcguffinitis, a disease that can only be cured with the rare plot device of healing. They set off on a grand, extremely short quest, and work together throughout in order to save their dad. Unfortunately, while the story has depth to it, its painfully obvious what is going to happen while you play, unless your a naive person who can't recognize tropes when they see them. This effectively kills the narrative, which is the only thing it has going for it aside from the semi interesting set pieces throughout the game.The gameplay is simple, very simple in fact. Your controller (if you play with a controller, and you should) is split in half, one side controls one brother, the other controls, well...The other brother. Each stick moves its respective bro, and one of the bumpers makes them interact with the nearest object in the world. You can rotate the camera as well, but you don't really need to. Through this you solve easy puzzles. Alot of them are quite creative, but none of them are difficult.This is a game that, through its mechanics, makes you feel for the characters, and what it tried to achive is admirable. But, for me at least, the moment I started playing the game, I knew exactly how it was going to end. This killed the entire experience for me and made it entirely unsatisfying, because without the narrative, the gameplay feels weak and lackluster. As it stands, the game is a great proof of concept, that you feel more for the characters you play as, and you feel their loss the most when its loss felt through mechanics of the game. For some people, thats perfectly fine, its a short, sweet game that is well executed. But for me, it was disappointing.I can't recommend this game at full price, at best maybe half price or less. Its the kind of game you play as a sort of palette cleanser, or, if your the emotional, sappy type, the kind of game you play to be hit right in the feelings. If your cynical like me, you wont enjoy this, and its only worth your time if your trying to find examples of mechanics and story blending together perfectly.  If your none of the above, don't bother with this title."
