,Recommended,225080,16929097,"Posted: 7 July, 2015",all,ErickaUnlimited,"OverviewBrothers - A Tale of Two Sons is a simplistic, yet provoking game in which you play as two brothers (simultaneously) on a quest to rescue their father from an unknown ailment. The story, character backgrounds and even your mission are shrouded in an unknown (probably gibberish) language, forcing you to rely on what the character's body language and surroundings are telling you. While it may seem difficult at first, the game does a marvelous job of keeping you on track and never feeling truly lost. It's a delicate balance that the game does quite well. I never felt lost, scrambling for what to do next.Without delving too much into the plot (for fear of giving away any spoilers), the story is straight forward, but very powerful. As the game progressed, I couldn't help but feel connected to the brothers, their family and the cast of characters you meet along the way. Without language, you're not so much being told what is happening, but experiencing it first hand, which was a treat.Visually, the game is filled with eye candy. The environments are beautiful and change drastically as you progress, letting you see a plethora of sights - from charming villages to the aftermath of a war zone. It's as visually appealing as it is thought provoking. Overall, the game is enjoyable, albeit short. If you enjoy puzzle games with some emotional storytelling, I would highly recommend this game to you.ProsStorytelling - The game has a unique way of guiding you without giving itself away. It's a refreshing alternative to spoken word.Visuals - The landscape is ever-changing, but always enjoyable. It leaves you with wonder and lets you fill in the gaps with your imagination.Interaction - Whether it be with other characters, animals or the environment itself, the game lets you interact with the world around you to let you understand each brother's personality.Music - Simply put, the music is an auditory joy to listen to.ConsGame Length - The game is short. I completed it in roughly 3.5 hours in one sitting. Some might be okay with that, some not so much. I was really hoping for more once I became invested in the characters.Difficulty - I found the game to be rather easy. I expected the puzzles to become progressively more difficult as the game carried on, but found they plateaued rather quickly.Overall, the pros heavily outweigh a few cons in my opinion. This one easily goes into my games recommendation list. It's a pleasure from start to finish, but remember to bring a a few tissues with you just in case."
76561197986527965,Not Recommended,225080,21614053,"Posted: 3 March, 2016",all,Dasbooby,"I don't get the love for this game.  It's an ok game, but that's about the best that can be said for it.  The story is pretty straight forward, nothing wrong with it, but nothing that interesting about it.  The world is somewhat interesting, but nothing is explained or expanded.  It's simply go here, look at this new area, ok we're done here, now look at this new area, and repeat over and over.  The graphics are pretty, but I'm not a graphics ♥♥♥♥♥ so that doesn't matter much to me.  The game is short and linear, lasting around 2 1/2 hours, and you spend a lot of that time walking on straight paths to get to the next puzzle.  The puzzles are way too simple, there wasn't a single one that took more than 2 seconds to look at and figure out, and they are often repeated.  If they had spent a little time making some puzzles that took some thought, the game probably would've been more enjoyable.  Controlling each of the brothers seperately is an interesting concept, but it's not used to the full extent that it could've been.   The dual movement also results in occasional moments where you lose track of your control on the brothers and send them running off in random directions until you stop and think about what you're doing.  It's not a big deal but might explain why they went with very simple puzzles.Overall, there's nothing really wrong with the game, but I feel like I wasted my time.  The game doesn't do anything particulary well and there's no challenge to be found here.  Why people seem to enjoy it so much, I'll never know.  I guess people are mesmerized by no challenge games, pretty graphics, and pushing arrows impaled on some dead bodies for the third time."
,Recommended,225080,8644132,"Posted: 10 January, 2014",all,bonkr`,"If you're looking for a quick game to play, get Brothers: A Tale of Two Sons. It works best with a controller, but can be played with a keyboard. The gist of it is that you control two brothers simultaneously to solve puzzles and complete action sequences. It gets awfully clever on you, and there are only very minimal cues in the game. That is, it rarely tells you what buttons you need to press. In fact, you've only got the movement controls for each brother and a button to make each of them separately interact with stuff in the environment. There's dialogue but it's audible only in gibberish and only serves to convey character emotion and build on the personalities of the cast. Through the journey you come to know the characters by the quirky way you control them, i.e. you'll probably end up paying more attention to one brother, while the other larks off in some other direction (keeping track of two characters at once is deceptively difficult.)It's only a few hours long, but the price is right. It's almost criminal that during the last steam sale I was able to get it for something like $2.50. Normal price $15, it's actually on sale for $7.50 right now. Get it."
76561197983276232,Recommended,225080,8721258,"Posted: 15 January, 2014",all,RedSwirl,"Brothers: A Tale of Two Sons is basically Ico, except you control both Ico and Yorda at the same time. It features similarly well-designed puzzles that utilize an impressively intuitive control scheme as you run through a world that manages to tell a completely wordless story.I haven’t tried to play this game with a keyboard but I probably wouldn’t recommended it. On a 360 pad you control each brother with one analog stick, and each trigger serves as an “interact” button for each of them. Through this, Brothers puts you through what is every bit the classic adventure game in the Ico, Another World, and Prince of Persia tradition.Each brother has different abilities -- the older brother is stronger and can swim but the younger brother can fit in smaller places. Through this, Brothers manages to give you puzzles that are surprisingly ingenious despite not being very complex. None of the puzzles took me more than a few seconds to work out, but at the same time none of them felt stupid. I’m still not sure how Starbreeze struck that balance. You can see a similar balance in the storyline.The game’s Sims-style gibberish manages to communicate that two brothers -- one in the midst of adolescence and the other reaching the end of childhood, must go on a quest to find a legendary medicine for their ailing father. There’s a lot of other interesting and well-told stuff in there as the brothers meet ever-wilder characters on their journey.Similar to Team Ico’s games, Brothers also takes you through environments that immediately feel like they have stories of their own, like the aftermath of a battlefield or the wake of a natural disaster. Furthermore, the game doesn’t even tell you the full story of what’s transpired in front of you, it just let’s you infer things.The art direction in Brothers serves all these environments and characters well despite it being quite modest in the technical area -- no fancy effects or anything and the system requirements don’t list any recommended settings, only minimum. Everything is in a sort of round, chunky aesthetic which seems to play to the Unreal 3 Engine’s strengths similarly to Gears of War 3.Brothers is a very tightly-put-together little adventure game that hits the hallmarks of what it’s probably trying to evoke: inspired fairy-tale locales, smart-but-intuitive gameplay, and an emotional storyline that doesn’t rely too much on cut scenes or any text, though the whole game will last you no more than three hours."
