76561198007771866,Recommended,225080,10769050,"Posted: 24 June, 2014",all,Strikeman,"After been hinted by it of Totalbiscuit, I decided to buy it last year. After seeing Totalbiscuit and [AReV]BavarianGod and having them already pointing out their arguments in their respected videos, I wondered if any review would be adding any additional insight. So after some thinking, I thought: lets discuss what the game did for me.To me, the game was a joyous experience, with a twist. Due to the tone of the game being about hefty themes like love, companionship and fear. The hefty themes suggest that the game wants to have those themes be taken very seriously, and for me it did, though not in the extend it happened to the previous mentioned people.One note should go to my favorite (and often overlooked) part of a game is sound: Though it forgoes the use of speech, Brothers does a damn fine job to fill up this gap by using gibberish talks, hand and feet communication and an awesome soundtrack (which you should buy btw) to provide the wholesale immersion.This game felt like a game again, not someone who has set some knobs regarding which few game mechanics should be in a game, press 'create' and voila: a triple-a title.No, this game seperates itself from that, in which it succeeds really well: its gameplay really let you immerse into the world, even though you're not seeing it from a first person view.All in all, I think that this game is for people who dare step off their beloved franchise game, try a single game and find this one.Ups:+ Good Narritive+ Heartfelt Story+ Unique Game mechanics+ SOUND!+ MUSIC!Downs:- Short Story- Difficulty"
,Recommended,225080,11565805,"Posted: 5 August, 2014",all,Zuluf,"I dont know whether whimsical thumbstick adventure is a genre or a thing or whatever, but to say that Brothers: A Tale of Two Sons is just that would be an injustice towards the title. Its minimalistic yet rich storytelling draws children of all ages in and while it offers little replay value and only lasts for an afternoon, it still qualifies as a gem. Lush, vibrant summits surround the two brothers gone on a quest to heal their father. The puzzles are pretty simplistic and the only initial difficulty will probably be struggling to teach your brain which thumb is which character, but the streamlined journey is less about overcoming challenges and more about watching the plot unfold.BUY it if you:- Own a controller- Value storytelling and polished art direction over all other aspects of a game- Would like an indie (alternative) structure with a high-end art direction.DO NOT BUY it if:- You expect long hours out of every dollar you spend on games.- You cannot abide a lack of replay value / violence / difficult puzzles- Your eyes may feel abused and slightly inflamed after exposure to Brothers: A Tale of Two Sons. This may especially be a problem if you wear contact lenses or big horse blinkers. Ask your video game dealer to suggest some less visually demanding entertainment immediately."
