,Recommended,225080,9272365,"Posted: 26 February, 2014",all,Aeolian Mode,"*me screaming at game* HOW COULD YOU DO THIS TO ME?*ahem*Okay, let me give this game a more satisfactory review.(Mild spoilers below)When I was a film student in college, my film professor loved hammering in this idea to his students: sound is everything. And lack thereof. He prefers silent films for this reason: visual storytelling should not rely on sound to create the story. Sound should be a suppliment to that story, not a crutch. And, when done right, the right sound effects in the right place can drastically heighten emotional impact.Good sound design is one of those things that often goes unnoticed in film and game critique. And Brothers has good sound design.The lack of understandable dialogue actually makes the story better because it forces us to discern the story from simple action alone. Oftentimes I found myself rationalizing the actions of the brothers and other NPCs by determining their emotions from their actions. Such as the crying forest giant- context allowed me to discern that someone he loved was gone. That was just one example of many I found myself thinking as I played the game. Don't give your audience 4: give them 2+2. Let them figure it out. That's why this game doesn't need dialogue.The music only has a discernable melody and composition when in emotionally intense situations. Otherwise, it is atmospheric, indecipherable sounds. This is effective because if a musician relies too much on bombarding our senses with fantastic melodies at all times, we will not be able to appreciate a moment when it truly calls for some riveting emotions. So, when you're just wandering the land, accomplishing small tasks, the music remains quiet, pensive, and ambient. When something big is going on... it's spine-chilling. Contrast is everything!The sound effects are immersive because they draw from the environment, and you can often hear things coming before you see them. This is effective because when you are traveling around in real life, out in the woods or even on city streets, oftentimes you will hear things before you see them coming. This is something we have tended to take for granted, but you can tell this was intentionally designed in the game.Of course, the art direction was gorgeous. I especially love the fact that the characters are not rendered in an attempt for photorealism like many triple A titles these days. You simply don't need that. Stylized, abstracted forms are more pleasing to the eye IMO. Attempting photorealistic characters in a video game is just too uncanny valley for my tastes.The *colors*, man. The light and shadows. The composition. It's a visual masterpiece.And the ending. I don't have to explain why it's so chilling and amazing.What are you waiting for... buy this game!"
,Recommended,225080,14216955,"Posted: 28 January, 2015",all,AllTracTurbo,"I don't think I could say anything about this game that hasen't been said in the other 13,700 positive reviews at the time of writing this. This is an absolutely beautiful and atmospheric game. If you think there is any chance you might enjoy this type of game, just get it, you won't regret it. It's a little short at 4 to 5 hours, but it's worth it.The game was designed for an xbox 360 controller. You can play with a keyboard, but you will have a problem at 2 parts in the game. You can get through these parts, but you will have to hold a button down for a few minutes at those 2 parts instead of about 10 seconds. You can use other dual stick controllers (I used a PS2 controller), but you will probably need to use a small free program called x360ce which is an xbox 360 controller emulator. This will tell the game you are using an xbox controller and the program will let you map the keys on your controller. If you are using a PS2 controller and the right stick doesn't map correctly, search online and there is a patch that will fix it."
