,Recommended,225080,24110647,"Posted: 5 July, 2016",all,Thetigerisariver,"I often find myself disinterested in strongly story-focused videogames. If I wanted to read or watch a story unfold, I would pick up a book or a movie, respectively.But I completely adored Brothers.Why do we love stories? Personally I think it's because we look to stories for reflection of our experiences, and we love to be emotionaly manipulated. Brothers will make you feel all kinds of emotions, leading you to associate your controler's sticks and buttons with it's characters. I felt commited not to let my fingers slip in dangerous situations, even though I have hand problems and it hurt my wrists.Brothers is also fundamentally a classic fairytale - it's magical and grim; it's characters are confronted with hardships that are often unfair, and everything it has to say about human condition feels very true. You will encounter all kinds of situations that hint at the wider world and what it is like, but without explicit lore, you can only guess at what is going on. After all, your characters are children and even the older one barely understands how the world works.I would rather end the review here, than risk spoiling this amazing game for you. Let me just reiterate that it touched me deeply and I honestly would recommend it to basically anyone."
76561198107966850,Recommended,225080,19520637,"Posted: 6 December, 2015",all,The Walkin Dude,Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons is an excellent example of a game that leaves an impact on you. You will play plenty of games over time but none quite like this title.The game at it's core is a adventure/puzzler and does a great job at giving you a great sense that you are exploring a beautiful fantasy world. I would personally love to see a book written in this world. The story is simple but effective and the game play itself is fun.My only gripe with the title is that there isn't more of it! The game can be clocked in around the 2 hour mark maybe 3-4 if you are an achievement hunter. It would have been great if the title was a little more lengthy and gave you say 10-15 hours. But none the less it was an enjoyable game and I encourage those that are curious to give it a go.
76561198025237822,Recommended,225080,10938755,"Posted: 29 June, 2014",all,Tamiant,"By far one of the most immersive, emotional experiences i've ever had in a video-game. The gameplay while odd at first, is definitely intuitive that adds to the overall experience, the puzzles are challenging and garner a sense of accomplishment upon completion. Though the game lacks any real dialogue (aside from gibberish and hand gestures) the story is an emotional roller-coaster that perfectly blends the two mediums of gameplay and story-telling that leaves a mark when the credits are rolling, I felt that this is one of the very few games that created a real emotional connection.Before you say anything, no this isn't like The Walking Dead or Limbo, games that have recieved a large amount of backlash in the sense that they're not real games, but interactive stories, that is not the case with Brothers. You live the story, you don't sit back and watch thirty minutes of cutscenes with a little bit of game-play in between, a great example of this without spoiling anything, is towards the final act of the game. A scenario which could've easily been shown through a cutscene is instead fully playable, you live out this moment which undeniably leaves a major impact. I've never written a review on Steam before, but after completing this game I was compelled.The game possesses a beautiful  art style that brings out a wonderful yet dark world complemented by a soundtrack that gave a sense of 'awe' that fully captured and immeresed me in these brother's journey.Without a doubt the best $3 i've ever spent I can't reccomend this game enough, grab it while it's cheap. The game will take you around three hours to complete (which is a perfect length for this title) and I reccommend you finish it in one sitting. Lock your doors, switch off your phone, and enjoy the masterpiece that is ""Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons"".P.S. Play with a controller, this game was definitely made for it."
76561198060634908,Recommended,225080,13885644,"Posted: 7 January, 2015",all,omally72,"I held off playing this game for a long time because it claims to require a controller, which I can't stand using most of the time, and because it was published by 505, who published Payday 2 and How to Survive - neither of which I enjoyed.  This game was quite the pleasant surprise, though.  First off, a controller is not required; using a keyboard can be a bit awkward at times, but will work just fine.  Second, unlike How to Survive, there were no game-breaking bugs, meaning I actually got to finish the game, and I'm glad for it.  This was an amazingly innovative platformer with beautiful artistic design and a well-told story.  It's brief, but it doesn't need to be any longer than it is - in fact, trying to stretch things out to pad the length would have hurt the overall experience.  The puzzles aren't too complicated, and are all very logical - the challenge comes in controlling 2 characters at the same time, who need to work together to solve the puzzle.  It's one thing to play a game like Portal 2, where you and a friend have to work together, but having to work both brothers at once takes some getting used to.  It's a completely unique mechanic I don't recall ever seeing before now, and it was a fascinating way to play the game.  The entire story is told without a single line of dialog - there is a language being spoken, but it's gibberish and you're not meant to understand it.  Everything is conveyed via gesture and inflection, the mood is set through the music, and it's all done very well.  It helps that the story is very simple and straigtforward - this game is about the journey, the bonding and the loss, and the spectacle of it all, and to that end it was very well crafted.  I'd say it's definitely worth a playthrough."
