,Recommended,225080,8394743,"Posted: 29 December, 2013",all,Alan Parsons,"Awesome environments, characters, interactions, aesthetic, controls, design, everything. It is short, so don't spend time watching reviews and whatnot. The less you see beforehand the more you will enjoy it."
,Recommended,225080,7988819,"Posted: 9 December, 2013",all,Hatsuna,"Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons is exactly as the title suggests, the story of two boys, connected by the bonds of brotherhood, unified in their quest to find a cure for their dying father (this is relayed to the player in the first minute or so of the game).  From the moment we pick up the controller (more on this later), we too, are tied to these boys.  We guide them forward, facing the adventure that lies ahead.Brothers is in every way an experience refined to its most vital, leanest, core.  There is no dialogue to read, no complexity or depth to the controls, or even mindblowing technical detail to the environments.  What we have instead is not by many standards an objectively better game, but one which utilizes its design choices to create an incredibly engaging and meaningful experience.Brothers’ story is “told” to the player through an almost primal but ultimately simple and refined manner.  No English nor any known language is spoken (as far as I know) in the world in which our fated brothers inhabit.  Instead, the intonation of the voice and the expressions displayed by the characters serve as the primary method of narration.  In this way, engaging our senses without having language and words to get in the way, we begin to empathize at a core emotional level with the brothers and the people around them.  Wanting to smile at the sound of their laughter; tensing at moments of stress, tearing at moments of pain.  Without “telling” us anything, Brothers makes us feel.  And that in itself is an achievement.Upon recommendation, I was told to play Brothers using a controller.  After playing through Brothers, I can understand why such a recommendation was made.  The controller is split in half, one action button, a camera button, and an analog movement stick for each brother.  In this way, each brother feels like an extension of the self.  As you struggle to coordinate the movements of your own hands, you watch as they too, struggle to work together.  As you improve, so do they, traversing the terrain with the ease of a well oiled machine.  In this way, running, tiptoeing, sneaking around, moving in general just feels good in analog, as it should.And while Brothers is by no means a technically impressive game, it does pull off awe inspiring spectacle.  The terrain is highly varied, puzzles never overstay their welcome, and moments of pure exhilaration and smile inducing giddiness play at odds with true moments of adversity, rounding out the experience as a whole.  In this way, the variance of the environments reflects the range of emotion that occurs in Brothers.  Wrapped in what in hindsight looks like a 2-3 hour rollercoaster ride, but in the moment, felt like days of adventuring, Brothers is an experience worth having.  Not to watch someone else experience, or to even read about, but to have and experience and live yourself."
