,Recommended,225080,11694749,"Posted: 13 August, 2014",all,I Got a Rock,"WARNING: SPOILERS WILL BE COVERED BY BLACK BOXES LIKETHIS. IF YOU DO NOT WISH TO SEE THEM, DO NOT MOUSE OVER THEM.After replaying through this game again a few nights ago, I realize that I still haven't written a review for it. Well, better late than never (holy crap, it's already been almost a year?!).If I were to run into you on the street, and (for God only knows what reason) you wanted my overall thoughts on the game in a single sentence, I'd tell you, ""I don't know why you're talking to me and not playing this game.""I'm not exaggerating when I say thatBrothers: A Tale of Two Sonsis the best indie game and possibly the greatest game I have ever played.Honestly, if you're just reading this to see if the game's worth $15, take my word for it.I would refuse to pay a cent less for such a fantastic game.For those who don't know,Brothers: A Tale of Two Sonsis a short adventure puzzle platformer in which each half of your controller (or keyboard, as I hear does work, but I'd imagine it's a bit wonky) controls a separate character - brothers Naia (older - left half) and Naiee (younger - right half). As far as I'm aware, the game is virtually glitchless, although I did have an instance where Naiee fell through the floor and died while picking up a turtle for a sidequest. Speaking of the quest, it's actually incredibly linear, but not in a bad way. The game's layout could not be better suited for the story. Not EVERY game has to be ""like Skyrim with guns"" as the saying goes. The gameplay is innovative and even plays a crucial role in the story. SPOILER TAG:""A friend is one soul in two bodies."" -AristotleWhen the creator tried getting companies to publish the game, he said it's a singleplayer experience in the guise of a co-op game. Thank God Starbreeze came along and took interest in the game, else we wouldn't have this masterpiece to talk about. However, personally I played this with a friend sharing a controller the first time through, and I would have to disagree. It's equally as great either way. With a friend, it's easier to manage, having to only focus on one character, and the storyline immerses you into creating almost brotherly bonds. However, it's just as good to play alone, because you can experience the story the way it was intended - by not fearing to shed your manly tears in front of your comrades.Speaking of which, the story is written by Josef Fares, a Swedish film writer who had a really rough childhood. SPOILER TAG:Remember the ending burial scene? Of course you do. How the hell could you forget something as touching as that? It turns out that was a childhood memory of Fares'. He always wanted a little brother, so when his mother went into labor, he was so excited. In the end, the baby died, so Fares had to bury it himself. Try thinking aboutthatnext time you play that part and try not to cry.For those who haven't played the game and are avoiding the spoiler tag, I apologize for tempting you with the enormous spoiler box. Needless to say, Fares' past experiences had a huge impact on his works, so despite what you may think, it may look cute, but there is a monster hidden within. With several instances of morbid scenes and scenery hardly scattered throughout, this game rightfully deserves its rating of T for Teen.The graphics are some of the best I have ever seen in any game ever. Screw Battlefield 4, Skyrim, or any other stereotypical games with ""realistic"" graphics. Despite having a cartoonish feel to it,Brothers: A Tale of Two Sonshas the most atmospheric landscape of any game I have ever played. Water, foliage, shadows and sunlight, everything looks absolutely incredible. But every aspect of this game has something morbid or sad, and the graphics are no exception. Have you ever played an FPS and thought about how unrealistic blood looks? In this game, blood looks disgustingly realistic. I gagged a little bit in the land of the giants. At one point, you have to push a corpse holding an axe to chop an arm off that is blocking your path. It's incredibly morbid, and you should expect nothing less from this game.And finally the soundtrack. Whether the mood of a scene is sad, happy, epic, or scary, the music is always there to accompany it in perfect harmony (see what I did there?). With its orchestral, cinema quality soundtrack,Brothers: A Tale of Two Sonsuses music to make you feel the emotions that characters would feel as if these scenes had happened to you. In a story driven game like this, a fitting soundtrack isessential, because unless you are like Fares, you can't relate to all these dark and depressing events, and an emotional soundtrack can give you a push. Obviously, this feeling is nothing close to how it would be if these thingsactuallyhappened to you, but it's probably as close as we would ever want to be.TL;DR: The game's graphics, soundtrack, gameplay, and most of all storyline are all phenomenal. Don't be fooled, this game is dark. It's a bit short at around 3 hours, but it's fun to replay and reexperience the overwhelming emotions it will give you.Overall rating: 10/10"
,Recommended,225080,11008782,"Posted: 1 July, 2014",all,Ʌ𝘚𝘊𝘕𝘋𝘙.,Well worth your time. A 3 hour puzzle game with an interesting story and playstyle. The ending is inspiring. BUY IT
,Recommended,225080,8718076,"Posted: 15 January, 2014",all,Jonahsniper,"No doubt this is my Best Game of the Year 2013.Don't be fooled by its anime style art, this is a sad story about death, spirit, move on and growe up.Have some hilarious and excitement moment, also have touching scences that move you, especially when you have to ""interactive"" with.No doubt it's graphic and music are on the top list compare with other games this year. Too many stunning views make you forget this game made by a normal engine.Did I mention gameplay yet? The control needs a little time to used to, even in the middle of the game, I still have some clumsy time moments. But this game allows you make mistakes and try again without penalty. Some puzzles are challenging but full of hint, the developer didn't intend to make you smash the controller for stuck in a tough puzzle with days. Thay want you to enjoy and interact with the story, with amazing visual and beautiful score come great atmosphere. How could you not love this game?"
