,Recommended,225080,8390678,"Posted: 29 December, 2013",all,Rumblemuffin,"I had picked up this game mainly because I kept hearing it brought up constantly during the Giant Bomb GOTY deliberation podcasts. It was something that was completely off my radar.I cannot describe how spectacular this game looks. Each ""Level"" had its own atmosphere and the transitions between areas does not feel forced. It provides for a fluid flow through the game. It is something that will need to be experienced firsthand in order to appreciate it. Even the game realizes this by providing small moments where you can just take in the scope and detail of the scenery. All of this is exemplified by a truly outstanding score to go along with this game, I had played through with a decent set of headphones and throughout the entire game the music just added into the experience in a very impactful way.Game play is a little odd to get used to. A controller is a must, while there were keyboard mappings in the options you control each brother with the separate analog sticks. It takes some getting used to, and even towards the end I was still confusing the two onscreen on screen with the controls getting their positions reversed. But it ultimately gets the job done, I had never found myself blaming the controls.This was something I finished in a single sitting. I think that is the best way to experience this due to the nature of the gameplay. The motivations for the character seem a little weak, where you are attempting to cure your sick father (Which you get very little screen time with at the start of the game) and you set off on an adventure. The charm of the environment and the pacing through the game bring everything together even with the loose story creating an ultimately enjoyable runthrough.Put on some headphones, grab a controller and set aside a few hours and just enjoy the experience."
