,Recommended,225080,8941845,"Posted: 1 February, 2014",all,anthony,"Having never written a review before, it seems only fitting that my first be a review of Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons, for I can, with no reservations, say that this is my favorite game. Let it first be understood that I have an affinity for casual games with unique elements. That being said, Brothers has everything that I look for in a game: an interesting plot, a unique game mechanic, and a beautiful universe, among many other things. The first thing you notice about the game is the truly unique control system. The player controls two people simultaneously using the two analog sticks and just two buttons. This takes some getting used to but the game eases you into it before throwing tough puzzles that require some rather ambidextrous fingerwork at you, all the while providing you with a great soundtrack and one of the most beautiful and interesting surroundings. The world these two prothers live in is never said aloud but it was most likely inspired by the game writer's Nordic home. Although the brothers start in a small coastal village, they soon journey throughout their world, passing through neighboring towns, trolls' fortresses carved into mountains, cities inhabited by only frozen citizens and invisible giants, and even an epic battle fought between men taller than mountains. In each new place the boys enter, they try to save someone in need, or avoid getting sacrified, eaten, or frozen. It is worth noting that throughout the entire game, not a single word is spoken in any understandable language. Despite this, the game manages to elicit intense emotions as the brothers struggle with the world around them, those they meet, and each other on their quest to save their father. I have no shame in admitting that I may have shed a tear at the end. Overall, this game is one of the best I've ever played and would recommend wholeheartedly to anyone looking for an adventure of a lifetime."
