76561197969948149,Recommended,225080,13764919,"Posted: 1 January, 2015",all,BigEyeGuy,"One SentenceA wonderful, short, and aptly priced 3D platformer with a twist.A Bit MoreControlling both characters is a great concept which keeps the simple (sometimes a bit too simple) platforming parts interesting. Story is wonderfully delivered with lots of small moments to pay attention to and absorb.Even experienced gamers will find them selves confusing the controls between the brothers but that should not be a big hurdle. One thing to note is how physical the game could get when using a controller as you will be holding the shoulder buttons for dear life in certain segments.Bottom LineInstead of providing 20+ hours of enemy killing and huge stages ""Brothers"" provides 3 hours of amazing story telling and  solid gameplay that will stick with you.Highly recommended.Followhttp://steamcommunity.com/groups/West7for more game reviews"
,Recommended,225080,14040916,"Posted: 17 January, 2015",all,Doctor Teo,"If you were dismayed that you were never able to play Journey because it was a Playstation exclusive, or played it and wanted more, look no further: Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons is the Journey for the PC platform.The characters are silent but expressive. The environments colorful and vibrant, yet at times dark and twisted. The path is straightforward, but full of hidden secrets along the way. This is not a game of reflexes and precision - there is no user interface to distract the player from everything that goes on. This is one of those fancy shmancy 'all about the experience' games; if you're not the type of player who likes a slower paced game, Brothers will not appeal to you. However, if an odyssey through gorgeous unknown lands with a silent storytelling scheme sounds like your kind of game, Brothers is the kind of game where you can get lost in.The game is played from the perspective of the two Brothers, controlled simultaneously. Despite the label, you do not need a controller to play this game; keyboard alone will work fine, though a controller will feel more natural. The two brothers have only two actions: moving, and a context-sensitive action button. It may not seem complex, but when you coordinate the two brothers at once to navigate puzzles, a single action button per brother is plenty. The brothers may move in similar fashion, but you soon learn they have their own strengths, which I will not spoil as some of them are story-centric.And did I mention the environment is astounding? There are countless hidden secrets and interactables, with the two brothers reacting differently to most of them. Everything in this game is hand-crafted and visually stunning. No lens-flare, no blood-on-the-camera, just luscious amounts of scenery porn. If you're packing a good graphics card, this is where you'll be happy to have it.You would think a game where one controls two characters independently to be confusing, but it successfully creates a challenge rather than an annoying gimmick. Imaginative and inspiring, melding gameplay with adventure, Brothers is going to be a must-have for most people. If one wonders whether or not gameplay is art, wonder no longer - you'll be too engrossed in this game to care.The only criticism is the stupid lever at the start of the game. God damn that lever.The game is also pretty short; there's no doubt it's thorough, well-paced, and end at a good time, but it does leave one wanting to find more....P.S.: As a side note, the game can also be crudely played with two people, one controlling each brother. While it may take away from the mechanical challenge of having to control two entities, it throws in a fun teamwork element and allows you to enjoy the game with a second person. We played with one person on keyboard and another on controller, but having two people on keyboard is also possible. Since the game is not 'meant' to be played this way, you may find some parts easier or more difficult than normal, but I can attest that the game will still be satisfying to play."
,Recommended,225080,14613560,"Posted: 23 February, 2015",all,Alex/Liquid_soda #SlavLife,Amazing game.  A very emotional journey through unknown lands. 10/10
,Recommended,225080,8598066,"Posted: 6 January, 2014",all,Mellow,"Brothers: A Tale of Two Sons is a neat little game with a well-structured plot that is interwoven rather well with its novel control scheme. Unfortunately, however, it leaves much to be desired in terms of core gameplay.Despite the presence of weak puzzling and platforming elements, Brothers: A Tale of Two Sons is little more than a “press forward to win” game albeit one with a somewhat interesting, but often derpy, control scheme. I used a gamepad on my playthrough and found the controls to be quite intuitive for the most part. If Lefty/Righty finds his way to the right/left of his sibling, however, what was once practical quickly becomes a derpfest of wrestling with the controls. It's not particularly bothersome but it does serve to emphasise how, with a duration of just two to three hours, I barely had time to get comfortable with the controls. Yet, in this short time, I still found many elements of gameplay tedious and repetitive. Expect to slog through the same “puzzle” several times in quick succession and spend most of your time moving forward unchallenged by NPCs or the environment.Without any sense of challenge or urgency, I felt like I was just going through the motions and waiting for the climax. I believe the pay-off in the final stages of the game was fantastic but the larger experience left me unsatisfied.The story itself was fine and characterisation was done quite well, and rather innovatively, despite the short play time. The use of a gibberish non-language throughout, however, really detracted from what might otherwise have been emotive moments. I laughed when my characters were frustrated, upset or afraid and I urged them to STFU when they expressed their anguish.Looking back on some of the screenshots I took, there were many areas that struck me visually and I thought the art direction was beautifully executed. One visual gripe I have with the game is that every time there is a cutscene, a substantial portion of screen real estate is wasted on black bars. This was a design choice and one that audiences, as I certainly did, may find jarring throughout their time with the game. The intended audience of this game is a little murky; I kept thinking the gameplay might be well-placed in a game for children but that notion just doesn't sit well with the game's many grim tonal shifts.Overall, Brothers: A Tale of Two Sons is a technically polished game with a lot of potential but it's hard to recommend it on the basis of anything but its fleeting novelty.Unidimensional, unchallenging, mercifully short.Still worth a look."
