,Recommended,225080,8810978,"Posted: 22 January, 2014",all,Vehmeriino,"The game is an experiment that mostly works. It's NOT a Game of the Year candidate or an amazingly memorable tale like some critics would have you believe. I went in eyes blinded with hype, and came back surprisingly underwhelmed.It's a good game, don't get me wrong, but some people make it out to be something much more that it in truth is. Brothers: A Tale of Two Sons has a lot in common with this other game called Gone Home in fact. Both were released in the same year, both were hyped to kingdom come upon release, both are about 2 hours long and both leave you somewhat satisfied, but also disappointed that the game is unable to carry the large amounts of hype it received.But what about all the praise it received? Am I bashing this highly rated game just to sound edgy? No. I personally could not connect much with the story or characters because of the lack of dialogue. At no point I also became accustomed to the weird controls of the game. I was playing with a gamepad as was recommended, but from start to finish it was very hard and at points frustrating to move the main characters. I didn't die because of the controls though, because the game rarely even lets you fail. It's pretty straightforward from point A to point B running, but the controls are a constant hindrance.I know it is the point of the game that there's no understandable dialogue between the characters and the controls are supposed to be hard to grasp. It doesn't still make it OK even if it was designed that way, because it annoyed me as a player of the game personally.In conclusion it still gets a recommendation, but I had very mixed feelings about the game."
