,Recommended,225080,12236866,"Posted: 25 September, 2014",all,RPINerd,"I think it’s easy enough to skim through the other reviews and know that Brothers is a fresh, innovative, beautiful game with very few elements capable of being considered a flaw so instead I want to do my best to explain how it feels to play this game. Additionally, all of my game time was with a 360 pad and I cannot recommend enough that you use a controller when playing Brothers.The controls are about as straight forward as controls can be; left stick and left trigger move and interact respectively for one brother, right stick and right trigger controls the other brother. That’s it. Yet with only 4 controls this game pulls you in and makes you feel like a part of the world in a way I have not seen in a game before. I think because of the simplicity of the controls, your mind has more attention to invest in the story, the emotions and the world stretching out before you. I wish I could explain one of the most impacting moments of the story without giving any spoilers, but there comes a point late in the game where the controls change in a very deliberate way and there are not enough words on this earth to explain how heavy of an emotional impact that change made.Brothers: A Tale of Two Sons is one of the finest adventures in gaming that I’ve been on, but when you combine the game with the absolute masterpiece of a control scheme it’s no longer an adventure I played.. it’s a memory that I lived."
