76561198081783772,Recommended,225080,8762509,"Posted: 18 January, 2014",all,Ninjadude,"Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons is a game that should not be judged for its gameplay that being said the controls can really mess with your brain at points and even up until the end of the game I never really adapted to the controls.  There are some points though when the gameplay is very enjoyable and the puzzles, although never actually difficult, leave you saying ""huh, that's interesting""The real strength of this title however, is it's stunning presentation from the story to the visuals to the amazing score.  They say actions speak louder than words and that is very true in this case.  There's very little dialouge in the game and when there is, it's in a nonsensical language, but even though you can't understand what they're saying the dialouge is meant for you to hear the emotions in their voices.  It is very much an interpretive game.  My favorite part of the game however were these mini areas off the beaten path that had there own little story to tell.The graphics are stunning and there are benches scatter throughout the journey that allow you to sit and bask in the scenery.  The lighting and water physics are absolutely gorgeous and make the atmospheres of each of the areas you pass is brilliant and the stark differences between them becomes a refreshing change from the last.The music in the game is always present, which is not a bad thing considering how great it is.  Every moment and every feeling you get throughout the game is greatly intensified because of the absolutely beatiful score.Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons is an amazing experience and, although you'd only replay it to find the small side areas, should be considered a game with brilliant execution and presentation"
