,Recommended,225080,11818936,"Posted: 22 August, 2014",all,Chaolance,"Brother's is something we don't see on the gaming scene that often.  A game that acknowledges the medium it is heavily and finds a way to marry its control scheme and narrative cohesively in a way that you just have to actually play yourself to understand how well it works.Controlling the Brothers is a unique experience not often done in games.  Each Brother moves and interacts with a thumbstick and a trigger (one half of the controller for each brother) and this takes some getting used to.  But the game trains you naturally to get used to it through the use of its gameplay without any handholding tutorial.  The brothers need each other to progress through the puzzles of the environment and diversifies the characters by giving them different abilities for the puzzle solving (i.e. the larger brother Nayaa can boost the little brother Nayee up to a higher ledge and Nayee can find a way to in turn help Nayaa up also).The game continually finds new ways to use its unique control scheme of two characters working together and it feels like a coop experience but everything is in sync because its a single person controlling both characters.The gameplay does an amazing job of reinforcing the story which in turn refuels the gameplay in this much more cohesive symbiosis between the two .  The story itself is set in a fantasy universe which people have compared to ICO and Fable series (which is a fair assessment) but they way you discover and interact with this universe is one of the best parts.  I'll try to avoid spoliers but the Brothers are setting out well beyond the borders of the town they are familiar with so their sense of discovery and wonder at all the worlds curiosities is also your own.  To reinforce this the games decided to not use an actual language but still include the concept of dialogue and its perhaps one of the best things about its story.  The interactions between the characters are so well done that despite not understanding a single word as a player you still know exactly what is being said in every exchange simply through the emotive body language and tone of the characters during the interaction and the context of the gameplay both preceeding and during each scene.  This less familiar method of storytelling makes the game a much more emotional journey that you experience as the characters themselves do.  Their highs and lows are your highs and lows and the story is incredibly moving as a result.  Its probably one of the best examples of player immersion you'll be able to find from any game really.So yes this game was an experience more than it was just any other game.  Don't spoil it for yourself by watching someone play it and don't let it pass you by.  Grab a gamepad (you really need one for this game I think the keyboard controls would unavoidably hamper the experience.), take an evening off (you'll only need one) and give it a go. This is one of those games that any gamer young or old, novice or veteran will have an incredible time playing through."
76561198059599584,Recommended,225080,14091572,"Posted: 20 January, 2015",all,Miggzy,"This game....The art made my jaw drop more than once. The music sent shivers down my spine, and the absence of music was always amazing for atmospheric effect. The control scheme is genious; I've seen the idea before, but never executed as well as in this game. All the images you see on this game's Steam page are gameplay. That's right. Not cutscene. Both of my parents, who aren't technophobes by any stretch of the imagination, but aren't really that in the loop when in comes to gaming, loved this game. And they never even played it. The emotional impack delivered in about four hours of gameplay is mind blowing.Though this game is meant to be played single-player, I'm sure it would be an equal, if not greater experience if it were play with a loved one, each player getting half of the controller. Now, I can't really recommend this game for CAD$17.00, but on sale for even 33% off and I say pick it up.Oh, and Steam? This game does not require a controller to play. Get your♥♥♥♥♥♥together.The only grippe I have with this game is that it's a little short. The achievements that you might miis on your first playthrough might help soften the blow, though."
