,Recommended,225080,9184672,"Posted: 19 February, 2014",all,WHAM,"A mother dies in a tragic accident, leaving the father caring for the family's two sons. When the father becomes ill, the sons set out on a journey to find the only medicine that can save their father. The journey takes them through some of the most well-designed, carefully crafted and lovingly detailed environments I have seen in a videogame so far.Brothers - A tale of two sons sports fairly simple cartoon visuals that work well without taxing your system with overtly complicated particle effects. The character animation gets it's job done in conveying emotion and mood throughout the game. I did encounter two or three broken animations, in which a characted failed to face the correct direction while animating, for example, but these few instances were easily forgiven.This game is truly a model of gameplay design. There are no silly inventory puzzles, no illogical conversation trees (there is no actual language in the game, as far as I can tell) and nothing crowding the gameplay with unneeded trivialities. Two sticks control the two characters and two triggets are used to get the characters to undertake actions ranging from climbing to jumping to pulling levers to helping one another swim across a dangerous current. The game sports quite low difficulty level, so if you are looking for a challenge, you will not find one here.The environments of the game, while they pass by quite quickly, deserve their own special mention. Each part of the world has it's own special story to tell and since there is no real spoken dialogue, the storytelling is done by the landscapes themselves. Several times I found myself asking questions, wanting to know more about the history of the places I visited, and while the game hint's at past events, it never really reveals all of it's secrets, leaving you with a mind full of wonderment and questions as you move on.I personally found some of the long emotional musical pieces somewhat grating after a while, but considering the overall length of the game I can't really complain that much.I can easily recommend this bite-sized, yet emotional and interesting, game to anyone looking for a classic fairytale in the form of a videogame.Playtime: 3+ hours (single playthrough)Ratings (1-10)Visual: 9Audio: 8Story: 10Gameplay: 9Overall: 8"
