76561198016184736,Recommended,225080,21665337,"Posted: 6 March, 2016",all,SheepSayMeh,"I played this game, and I was emotionally shaken.I had my girlfriend play this game. At some point she turned to me and said 'I can't handle this'.This game is in one way a 'gamers' game. It has a mechanic no other game has.It's also the only game I had my girlfriend play where she understood outright what she had to do.It's extremely well made and emotionally draining.That said, It's also very short (~7 hours for two playthroughs), but well worth the  5 euros/dollars you'll spend on it in a sale.It's also a great game to have your non-gamer friends/family/SO play to show that games are a great medium for storytelling."
,Recommended,225080,21616095,"Posted: 3 March, 2016",all,cloud_ishida,Wasn't really expecting the end of this game. Good and you'll finish it in one playthrough.
,Recommended,225080,21622512,"Posted: 4 March, 2016",all,VAL,"This is the first game that I bought and played on steam.Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons is a marvel of storytelling and clever gameplay and a must buy for players who enjoy such.The first thing that I should say is that unlike what the notice says on the store page, this game does not require a controller to play.Gameplay and story:During the game you control these two characters with the arrow and wasd keys as the camera adjusts itself to the area that you are playing. The game itself is relatively simple and linear, requiring the player to overcome easy obstacles in the way of the protagonists' journey to save their ill uncle. In the course of their quest, they assist others in need and grow closer as brothers. It is slightly challenging to get ahold of controlling the brothers simultaneously at the start of the game but becomes much more fluid and easy as you progress through the levels even with a keyboard. Complement to the controls, the challenges along the way begin to require more ingenuity as you learn to control the brothers.Graphics:The areas themselves are beautifully designed and the game pauses every once in a while to allow you to enjoy it. From climbing crumbling ruins to scaling massive caves the game uses every area to show you just how beautiful and well crafted it is.Sound:There is no major dialogue so to speak but everything in the game is clear without it using too many words. What the lack of dialogue gives way to is a wonderful soundtrack that captures the emotional range of the story in ways that dialogue would never have. As the game becomes darker the longer you play, the sounds and music mature likewise.Overall:On the front, Brothers may look like a simple, light hearted puzzle adventure for a casual player. Playing it, I've come to appreciate the subtle and fine ways that this game was made elevating it in quality above many of the other games that I play. The story and gameplay are simple, the music complements the graphics excellently, and the entire experience is an emotional journey as two brothers enter dark and dangerous worlds to save their family.I cannot recommend this game enough and constantly badger anyone who would listen. It is a quick (approx 6 hr) playthrough and the ending left me sobbing. I have to say, this is a different caliber of gaming. I've never experienced anything like it10/10"
