,Recommended,225080,9781369,"Posted: 10 April, 2014",all,Konvection,"I have always wanted a video game to make me cry.It is mostly my own fault as I tend to be a mechanics first, narrative second kind of player. I think it's rational enough considering that the medium should focus on the degree of interactivity first and then supplement that with a strong narrative. I wish that would happen more often.When a game focuses solely on its mechanics, the story tends to seem like an afterthought. This model has evolved over the years with new technology and larger budgets, but the primary problem is still present: there has yet to be a video game that has the perfect marriage of both. Like what Don Quixote is to books and Citizen Kane is to movies, there must be a game that can single-handedly shift this paradigm and create a new precedent. And in the most unexpected of places, I believe that I have discovered one of the most compelling narrative experiences of all time: Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons.Brothers was created by Starbreeze Studios, a developer who is not typically known for small, story-driven games sold at a $15 dollar price point. In fact, the majority of their most popular titles are first person shooters with the phenomenal Chronicles of Riddick: Assault on Dark Athena and PAYDAY: THE HEIST leading the charge. In addition to Starbreeze's development, Brothers was aided by visionary Swedish film director, Josef Fares. It was an unusual and ambitious notion to consider a film director to help create a video game, but Starbreeze felt it was necessary, and they were right.Brothers tells the story of two brothers, one young and one old, working together in an epic journey to save their dying father by obtaining the waters at the Tree of Life. The dialogue between these brothers is done through utter gibberish as opposed to recognizable language. I wouldn't call it gibberish in the traditional sense, though, as there are some common words, such as the names of the brothers, Naiee and Nyaa, which are words heard consistently throughout the story. However, at no point does the game try to translate the language that is being spoken. It does not rely on intelligible language to tell the conventional tale; you know what you have to do even if you do not understand what you are told, either through gestures or the way that the environment presents the problem. It tells a coherent and recognizable story through complete ambiguity, and that is a remarkable achievement.On a fundamental level, Brothers is a single-player cooperative adventure game. As dichotomous as it sounds, this cooperative mechanic is true as you control each brother individually. It’s remarkably simple. The older brother, Nyaa, is controlled by the top left analog stick of the Xbox 360 controller, whereas young Naiee is by the bottom right analog stick. I have never seen a controller used in such an unconventional manner. Most games have to adapt to the interface technology; they have to build games around the way the controller works. And, of course, Brothers does that as every game has to do that to some extent. However, what Brothers manages to do is create a game that is perfectly suited to its controls and takes full advantage of what that controller has to offer.The core mechanics of Brothers exist in its platforming, puzzle solving, and control of two characters at once. The puzzles in particular are a testament to Starbreeze’s mastery of the genre. They never overstay their welcome and are always supplemented with more challenging and varied obstacles. They are not necessarily difficult puzzles, but they are satisfying ones that take advantage of the game’s unique controls. For instance, there was one sequence in which both of the brothers are tied together by a long rope. Unlike the normal freedom of movement presented throughout the game, the rope creates a unique restrictive dynamic to many of the usual tasks in the game. It makes the usually-mundane act of movement a more alien and onerous undertaking. Brothers consistently shows that it is not afraid to challenge the traditional gameplay approach in hopes for a more engaging experience.Brothers delivers the most emotionally charged stories I have ever experienced within a video game. Have I cried at the movies before? Sure. Have I cried when reading a book? Absolutely. However, I have never felt such a powerful emotional reaction with any video game until I played Brothers — and I am thrilled to admit that. I not only cried, I experienced a full breadth of emotional responses including sadness, happiness, wanderlust, horror, and most importantly in a game about family, compassion. And all of these emotions are delivered in a fantastic and mature way that at no point ever feels forced. Everything feels genuine; and it elicits all of these emotional responses without ever telling you to feel in a certain way. It does not tell its story through exposition-laden cut scenes or a bunch of celebrity voice acting. It did it by simply showing you this thematically beautiful world and allowing you to get immersed and involved in it, and many games struggle to achieve that.Brothers, unfortunately, suffers from some problems. There is no real question about that. Most of the time it comes from the game’s rigid adherence to the physical location where each brother must stand when taking part in an action. The game requires that each of those characters stand in a set position, and if you are standing in the opposite position it will awkwardly swap them over and rotate the characters. To see such unnatural movements within a mechanically focused game like Brothers is jarring, and unfortunately it made for a less immersive experience at times. I would also heavily criticize the aesthetic of the game. While its art direction is serviceable, the actual graphical fidelity leaves something to be desired. There were a few textures that looked outright hideous, and the design of many of the character models felt uninspired. It then became glaringly obvious that Starbreeze allocated most of its resources to the design of the brothers rather than the fidelity of the world in which they inhabit. Nevertheless, in those spellbinding moments before the games conclusion, it is hard to remember what, if anything, was wrong with the game in the first place.The culmination of the Brothers experience lies in its masterfully presented ending.  It doesn’t just show you this powerful ending moment and expect an emotional response; it lets you play it. It lets you conduct this horrifying moment in its entirety. And suddenly, you realize that this game was never telling you a story; you were playing the story. Your journey was the story.And that’s when I cried."
,Recommended,225080,9706693,"Posted: 2 April, 2014",all,SneakyMcCoy,"What a beautiful game.  Stunning graphics, wonderful music, and an immersive world.  You play as two brothers, simultaneously, using a controller (yes, a controller is *highly* recommended for this game).  Control the older brother with the left joystick, and the younger with the right.  It's a mechanic I haven't seen done before, and it works wonderfully.  Never did I feel too pressured or flustered with the controls; they were intuitive and fit right in with the game.The story features no real dialect, and the characters speak their own language.  As a result, the story grows from interactions and gestures rather than dialogue.  This is one game that I think truly demonstrates what the video game medium can contribute to society and art that other media cannot, and so I would highly recommend it."
