,Recommended,225080,9414569,"Posted: 10 March, 2014",all,liorean,"There are not enough superlative adjectives to properly describe this game.This game is the best emotional experience I have ever had. This is a more impressive work of art than any book I have read, any music I have heard, any movie that I have seen. And I'll try to dive into why and try to explain it.First of all - while a lot of the story and emotions are told with graphics and music and gestures and gibberish dialogue, this game manages to make you emotionally invested in the characters both because you play them both at the same time, and you constantly have to cooperate and interact, but also because you develop your feeling for them as the mechanics of the game develop and changes. The real experience of this game lies in holding that controller in your hands. In fact, if you as a PC gamer don't have a controller, this game alone should be motivation enough for you to get one.Second - the game has gorgeous, fabulous, amazing, stellar, fantastic graphics design. It is cute and incredibly well made when it comes to the characters, they present their personality through an amazingly well developed series of animations and articulations of their own emotions and thoughts, and use plenty of body language. The environment is a gorgeous watercolour-style and you even have a specific game mechanic just to watch the surroundings in the form of benches to sit on. The game progresses through a diverse set of environs that are very vertical, which gives you an amazing world to look at in addition to the nearer parts you can actually go to and through, which are just as good looking. Waterfalls and rock trails and town environments and mountains and battlefields and castles and woods, the game is fantastic in every aspect. I would say maybe half of the entire game time, you are looking at a view that would very well deserve to be a dektop screenshot, because it just looks that good.Third - the game is full of interesting interactions with the world, of characters and items that build the atmosphere, and who reacts to what you do in a way that really fleshes out and makes everything feel more immersive. And when things get tense and your controller starts rumbling, it enhances an emotion and setting you are already feeling from what the game has already managed to express to you.Fourth - Brothers has an amazing atmospherical sound design, from the gibberish language that makes dialogue work entirely through how things are said rather than any content of what the character say, to the ambience that makes the settings and environs feel amazingly well developed, from wind to waterfalls to strange mechanical apparatus to characters in the background, to the soundtrack that couldn't be a better fit to the emotions of the moment.Fifth - the game lets you tell the story, cutscenes are only used for telling story in amazingly small and short bursts, the vast majority of the storytelling is made by you, on the controller, guiding Naiee and Nyaa through the world.Sixth - while the aesthetics of the game are nothing short of stellar, the mechanics are solid and very well put together. Animations and actions are snappy and the characters' movements are very much not only well connected to what you do, they also tell some of the story in the form of changing slightly to adjust to you for example swimming, or holding two ends of an item, to one of the brothers being hurt, or even his emotional state.Seventh - when it comes to storytelling and world building, this game has it all. When you play it, it will be the most immersive piece of storytelling you have ever experienced. The setting goes from cute and wondrous to tense and dangerous to playful to sinister to somber to gross to harmonic to bereavement. It tells a story of a fantasy world where the sinister and the playful live side by side, where carefree happy life is just a stone's throw away from wizards turnings armies into snow sculptures, giants waging war, wolves hunting you and sinister trees trying to kill you.To categorise, this game is a single player cooperative 3D puzzle platformer adventure game. It is not long, but it is meaningful. It is a piece of art.This is the single best piece of storytelling, the most emotional of all works of art, the most immersive game I have ever experienced, and I do not doubt that if you play it the right way, undisturbed and undistracted from the game and the controller in your hands, you will feel the same. I cannot praise it enough. This is the best game I have ever played. It is the first game that has made me cry from the emotions it conveyed. And I want you to experience that too.Don't watch it being played on youtube or twitch. Don't watch a friend play it beside you. Don't play it in an environment full of distractions and sounds and people that interupt you. Play it where you can fully enjoy it, find a time and room free of distractions, put headphones on and take the controller in your hands, and just play it. When in the game, don't rush through it. Take the time to sit on the benches, view the environments, interact with the people and animals and items, immerse youself in the world and the setting, and you will be rewarded with a highly emotional and beautiful experience in a way I don't think any other game does."
,Recommended,225080,10882101,"Posted: 27 June, 2014",all,Caii,"The game is very short. I only got 2 hours out of it. However, I found it quite different to games I usually play so it was nice to switch it up."
,Recommended,225080,10796437,"Posted: 25 June, 2014",all,bdlio,"Loved every moment of it!The game looks incredibly beautiful - almost every frame looks like a gorgeous painting.There's hardly any visible texture repetition, it all looks unique - it's one of those games where I'm just glad I got my computer also hooked up to a big TV screen to be able to take it all in.The story is simple but moving and there's no (english) spoken word in the entire game - it's all conveyed through gesture and mood and I think this really adds to the game and draws you in more than real words could.It's not a very long game (~5 hours) and neither the puzzles nor the control mechanics are really challenging but this does not take away from the game - for the time it lasts it stays fresh and enjoyable and offers a really good time.I'm sure it won't be long before I replay the game - 9/10."
76561198095141770,Recommended,225080,15317025,"Posted: 11 April, 2015",all,King Horse,"This game changed my life.Before playing Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons, I always wanted a brother. I was a quiet kid in school. I silently cried all the time. I went through a Goth phase, a Punk phase, and a Christ phase. But they were all band-aids over my wound which was not having a brother. Plus my mom was killed during a New Years Eve. My parents were partying really hard, and she was trampled by a zebra that had snorted drugs. My dad went to jail.Anyway, I was lost after high school. Sometimes I visited my dad in prison, but I didn't know what to do with my life. So I got a job at the nearby Krispy Kreme. I didn't eat any of the stuff we sold because I didn't want to die from what we injected into the donuts, but I put them on display and sold'em to other sad people. And, I kinda liked their sadness; but it wasn't brotherhood. I bet many of them had brothers.One day, while crying and playing Dota 2, a Mexican guy typed something about Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons and that I was a noob or something. I told him to eat a♥♥♥♥♥♥and reported him for being Mexican. We lost the match, and I cried. Then, when I closed the game, there it was, Brothers - A Tale of Two Sons. It was a game! About the joys of having a brother, it seemed; I had to play it.It turned out to be even more than what I thought it would. I won't spoil any details, but just know that it let me go through the entirety of what brotherhood must be in real life. Brotherhood with your own blood. And the ending—don’t worry, no spoilers--near the end of the game, something happens to your brother, my brother, and you get to do something to him. It was the best moment of my life.Since then I've quit my job at the Krispy Kreme. I've been at community college for almost a year now, and I have all A's. I don't even cry around other men anymore. All because of that random Mexican guy, mentioning this work of art. I now know what it’s like to have a brother.I used to cry every day. Since finishing Brothers – A Tale of Two Sons, I haven’t cried once."
